ariety of literary, psychological, philosophical, and religious contexts.Three introductory chapters on autobiography and Hesse set the stage for a chronological study. Then follows a penetrating analysis of the balance between biographical fact and confessional fantasy in Hesse's long career, from the failed autobiography of his first literary success, Beneath the Wheel, through the protracted midlife crisis of the grotesque Steppenwolf period, to the visionary autobiography of his magisterial fictional finale, The Glass Bead Game.Originally published in 1988.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors, Germany20th centuryvBiography. 0aAutobiographical fiction, GermanxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiography. 0aConfession in literature. 0aSelf in literature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAntinomy.  aAntithesis.  aApologetics.  aArthur Rimbaud.  aArthur Schopenhauer.  aAsceticism.  aAutobiography.  aBathos.  aBertolt Brecht.  aBildungsroman.  aBiography.  aCarl Jung.  aCivilization and Its Discontents.  aConfucius.  aCounterculture.  aD. H. Lawrence.  aDemian.  aDemimonde.  aDialectical materialism.  aDiary of a Madman (short story).  aDramatic monologue.  aExistentialism.  aFaust.  aFeuilleton.  aFiction.  aFriedrich Nietzsche